{"actual_usd":0.158635,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":190,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31157,"reply":"\"No—though I get why it feels like math refusing to behave.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square, buying half a beat to say it cleanly.* \"Christians don't mean three separate beings who happen to share a category called divinity. They mean one God in being, three in person: the Father is God, the Son is God, the Spirit is God, and yet the Father isn't the Son, the Son isn't the Spirit, and the Spirit isn't the Father.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench once.* \"If it were three centers of deity standing side by side, yeah, that'd just be three gods. Monotheism holds because God's being is one, not divided into thirds and not duplicated three times. The hard part is that 'person' there doesn't mean 'three human-style individuals'—which is exactly where our intuition keeps trying to drag it.\"","rolling_24h_usd":41.40084500000003,"run_id":"002cd36e-cefb-459d-b81b-8a692ee69fb3"}
